","1448–Male":"1448–Afdød","1400–Male":"1400–Afdød","1405–Female":"1405–Afdød","1448":"1448","1467":"1467","1422":"1422","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1421":"1421","1442":"1442","1472":"1472","1418":"1418","1405":"1405","Brockdish, Norfolk, England":"Brockdish, Norfolk, England","Blo'norton, Norfolk, England":"Blo'norton, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England"},"nl":{"1422–":"1422–Overleden","1422–Female":"1422–Overleden","1418–1472":"1418–1472","1442–1467":"1442–1467","1448–Male":"1448–Overleden","1400–Male":"1400–Overleden","1405–Female":"1405–Overleden","1448":"1448","1467":"1467","1422":"1422","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1421":"1421","1442":"1442","1472":"1472","1418":"1418","1405":"1405","Brockdish, Norfolk, England":"Brockdish, Norfolk, England","Blo'norton, Norfolk, England":"Blo'norton, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1422–":"1422–Deceased","1422–Female":"1422–Deceased","1418–1472":"1418–1472","1442–1467":"1442–1467","1448–Male":"1448–Deceased","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","1405–Female":"1405–Deceased","1448":"1448","1467":"1467","1422":"1422","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1421":"1421","1442":"1442","1472":"1472","1418":"1418","1405":"1405","Brockdish, Norfolk, England":"Brockdish, Norfolk, England","Blo'norton, Norfolk, England":"Blo'norton, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hales","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (widespread, especially in the southeast): from the genitive singular or nominative plural form of Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, recess’ (see   Hale  ).","Irish: when not of English origin, this may be a variant of   Healy   or   McHale  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hale","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived in a (usually remote) nook or corner of land, from Old English and Middle English <i>hale</i>, dative of <i>h(e)alh</i> ‘nook, hollow’, or a habitational name from a place so named such as Hale in Cheshire, Hampshire, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, Holme Hale (Norfolk), Hale Street (Kent), and Haile (Cumberland). In northern England the word often has a specialized meaning, denoting a piece of flat alluvial land by the side of a river, typically one deposited in a bend. See   Haugh  . In southeastern England it often referred to a patch of dry land in a fen. In some cases the surname may be a habitational name from any of several places in England named with this fossilized inflected form, which would originally have been preceded by a preposition, e.g. <i>in the hale</i> or <i>at the hale</i>. This surname is also established in south Wales.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Céile</b> (see   McHale  ).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Halle  ."]},{"name":"Hayles","meanings":["English:","variant of   Hales  .","variant of   Ayles   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Hailes","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Hailes in Colinton (Midlothian), originally in East Lothian, named from the Middle English genitive or plural form of <i>hall</i> ‘hall’.","English: variant of   Hales   (see also   Hayles  )."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":33,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Hales was born in 1422, in Blo'norton, Norfolk, England, her father, Edmund Hales, was 22 and her mother, Mrs. Edmund Hales, was 17. She had at least 2 sons with William Le Grys. She died in Brockdish, Norfolk, England."},"et":{"1422–":"1422–Surnud","1422–Female":"1422–Surnud","1418–1472":"1418–1472","1442–1467":"1442–1467","1448–Male":"1448–Surnud","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1448":"1448","1467":"1467","1422":"1422","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1421":"1421","1442":"1442","1472":"1472","1418":"1418","1405":"1405","Brockdish, Norfolk, England":"Brockdish, Norfolk, England","Blo'norton, Norfolk, England":"Blo'norton, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1422–":"1422–Kuollut","1422–Female":"1422–Kuollut","1418–1472":"1418–1472","1442–1467":"1442–1467","1448–Male":"1448–Kuollut","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","1405–Female":"14